<DocsLayout
  title="Limitations"
  description="Know the product boundaries before using MyPaas as the deployment control plane for a server."
>
  <section>
    <p class="overline">Product scope</p>
    <h2>Single-node by design</h2>
    <p>
      The MyPaas API, dashboard, Caddy, PostgreSQL, and project workloads share one
      host. The VM is a failure domain and a capacity boundary. MyPaas does not provide
      automatic failover to another server.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Explicit non-goals</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Public signup, hosted plans, billing, or metered usage.</li>
      <li>Enterprise tenant isolation, organizations, or broad team administration.</li>
      <li>Buildpacks or source-language runtime inference.</li>
      <li>Kubernetes, Nomad, Docker Swarm, or multi-node scheduling.</li>
      <li>High availability, multi-region deployment, or fully automatic horizontal autoscaling.</li>
      <li>A general managed database replacement.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Operational implications</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Implication</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Host outage</strong></td><td>The dashboard and all projects on that VM become unavailable.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Capacity</strong></td><td>CPU, memory, disk, build concurrency, and project count must fit the host.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Backups</strong></td><td>The owner must configure and verify local and off-host backups.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Static projects</strong></td><td>MyPaas publishes ready output; it does not run arbitrary framework builds.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>GitHub webhook</strong></td><td>The generated URL and secret must currently be added to GitHub manually.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Rollback</strong></td><td>Image rollback applies to successful Dockerfile and Compose releases, not static output.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Do not assume these features exist</h2>
    <p>
      The product requirements describe staged improvements, but documentation and
      deployment decisions should not assume the following are currently available:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Idle sleep and wake-on-request.</li>
      <li>Historical autosizing or automatic limit changes.</li>
      <li>Multiple replicas and automatic Caddy load balancing.</li>
      <li>Custom domains per project or branch/PR preview deployments.</li>
      <li>Automatic GitHub webhook registration.</li>
      <li>Backup restore UI, team collaboration suite, or chat notifications.</li>
    </ul>
    <aside class="note"><p>Use the repository changelog and release notes as the implementation record. Planning documents are not release guarantees.</p></aside>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
